title: Appointments to the Advisory Council on Food and Environmental Hygiene
content_text:
p>
The Government today (March 27) announced the appointment of Mr Felix Fong 
Wo as the chairman of the Advisory Council on Food and Environmental 
Hygiene. Mr Fong is a lawyer and has been a member of the advisory council 
since 2005. He is the Chairman of the Liquor Licensing Board and a member of 
the Town Planning Board. Mr Fong also serves on other public sector advisory 
and statutory boards and has extensive community service experience. The Government also announces the appointment of ten new members and the

re-appointment of five incumbent members to the advisory council for a term 
of two years from April 1, 2009 to March 31, 2011. The appointments were 
made by the Chief Executive.  The new members are: Professor Paul Chan Kay-sheung; Professor Thomas Chan 
Yan-keung; Ms Cheuk Fung-ting; Mr Allen Ho; Dr Ho Pak-leung; Mr Alan Lee 
Chi-keung; Dr Lilian Leong Fung Ling-yee; Ms Winnie Li Hiu-lee; Professor Lo

Yuk-lam and Professor Wong Po-choi.  The following is a brief biography of the ten new members: Professor Paul Chan Kay-sheung is a professor in the Department of 
Microbiology of the Chinese University of Hong Kong. Professor Chan has 
involved in research studies in viral oncology, viral epidemiology, etc and 
has published a number of articles on human herpesvirus and serologic 
diagnosis of SARS. He is also a member of the Scientific Committee on

diagnosis of SARS. He is also a member of the Scientific Committee on 
Emerging and Zoonotic Diseases.  Professor Thomas Chan Yan-keung is a professor in the Department of Medicine 
and Therapeutics, Faculty of Medicine, of the Chinese University of Hong 
Kong. He has a special interest in toxicological problems relating to food 
consumption and the importance of diet in the prevention and treatment of 
chronic diseases. He is also a member of the Expert Committee on Food Safety

chronic diseases. He is also a member of the Expert Committee on Food Safety 
and a member of the Expert Group on Melamine Incident. Ms Cheuk Fung-ting is the executive director of Kampery Group and has 
extensive experience in the food and restaurant industry. She is also the 
vice chairman of the Association of Coffee & Tea of Hong Kong and one of the 
founding members of the Hong Kong Federation of Restaurants and Related 
Trades.  Mr Allen Ho is the director of food safety and quality assurance of the

Trades.  Mr Allen Ho is the director of food safety and quality assurance of the 
Dairy Farm Group. He is also a member of the Expert Committee on Food Safety 
and has extensive experience in food safety and quality assurance. Dr Ho Pak-leung is an associate professor in the Department of Microbiology 
of the University of Hong Kong. Dr Ho is an expert in the field of 
microbiology and infectious diseases. He is also a member of the Scientific

microbiology and infectious diseases. He is also a member of the Scientific 
Committee on Infection Control.  Mr Alan Lee Chi-keung is an engineer by training and is an elected member of 
the Kwai Tsing District Council. He also serves on several public sector 
panels and is involved in different district committees relating to 
environmental and health affairs.  Dr Lilian Leong Fung Ling-yee is a medical doctor specialising in radiology. 
She is an ex-officio member of the Council of the Hong Kong Academy of

She is an ex-officio member of the Council of the Hong Kong Academy of 
Medicine as well as a member of the Dental Council of Hong Kong. She has 
also served on the Medical Council of Hong Kong and various committees in 
the Hospital Authority. Ms Winnie Li Hiu-lee is the vice chairman of the Hong Kong Federation of 
Restaurants and Related Trades. She is also a registered X-ray technologist. 
She is the director of several food trade companies. She has extensive 
experience in the food trade and knowledge on food safety issues and

experience in the food trade and knowledge on food safety issues and 
regulatory control of food businesses.  Professor Lo Yuk-lam is an expert in the field of biotechnology. He has 
served as the chairman of the Innovation and Technology Fund (Biotechnology 
Projects) Vetting Committee. He is a member of the Research Grants Council 
and an adjunct professor in the Department of Biochemistry (Science) of the 
Chinese University of Hong Kong. Professor Wong Po-choi is a professor in the Department of Information

Engineering of the Chinese University of Hong Kong. He is the Chairman of 
the Committee on Home-School Co-operation as well as members of the 
Education Commission and Family Council.  On the new appointments, a government spokesman said the new members had 
sound experience and expertise in the subject matters of the advisory 
council and had taken a leading role in their respective professions. They would contribute to the deliberations of the council by considering 
food safety and environmental hygiene issues from a broad public interest 
perspective and assisting the Secretary for Food and Health in formulating

perspective and assisting the Secretary for Food and Health in formulating 
relevant policies, the spokesman said. The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, welcomed the new members to 
the advisory council. He also thanked the out-going Chairman, Professor Yuen 
Kwok-yung, and the outgoing members for their professional advice and 
significant contribution to the advisory council. Prof Yuen will retire from 
the advisory council on April 1 after having served as the Chairman of the

the advisory council on April 1 after having served as the Chairman of the 
advisory council for six years. The advisory council is a non-statutory body established on April 1, 2000, 
to advise the Government on food and environmental hygiene issues. Its terms 
of reference are �V * To consider and advise the Secretary for Food and Health on policies 
relating to food safety, environmental hygiene and veterinary public health, 
and to monitor their implementation; * To advise Secretary for Food and Health on the regulation of farms, food

premises, food hazards and food composition; * To receive reports on the handling of major food and farm incidents; and * To advise Secretary for Food and Health on community education and publicity programmes for promoting public understanding of food safety and public responsibility for environmental hygiene.
